The Prague Stock Exchange plunges into the minus.
After the steep fall in the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange was able to correct the losses.
Transactions with the shares of EZ reached almost half of normal day-to-day business.
At the beginning of Tuesday’s business, the Prague Stock Exchange continued to collapse from Monday, when it fell by another six percentage points.
This time, the reason for the burglary was Wall Street.
In the Czech Republic, too, the market’s reaction to the result of the vote of the American House of Representatives, which it had refused to support a stabilisation plan for the financial sector there.
Fall of shares in Asia
On Tuesday, stocks on the Asian stock exchanges experienced a dramatic fall, although the indices were able to offset some of the losses over the course of the day.
Hong Kong’s Hang Seng Stock Exchange index lost nearly four percentage points over the course of the business day, but was able to offset some of the losses later, thus reducing the decline to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, which monitors the movement of Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, fell by 3.8 percent, while markets in Shanghai were closed.
The stocks on the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent, but then reduced the losses to 4.3 percent.
The stock market in Taiwan fell by 3.6 percent, according to the index there.
“The timing of the rescue in the US is uncertain and will affect financial markets worldwide,” said Hong Kong Monetary Authority chief Joseph Yam.
Hong Kong, although part of China, determines its monetary policy itself, i.e. independent of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as those in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, U.S. legislators should return to the negotiating table as soon as possible and pass the draft financial system support.
Otherwise, other countries would be affected by the collapse.
A Massacre of American Stocks
The U.S. House of Representatives on Monday rejected the plan to support the financial system, which should be spent up to $700 billion (nearly $12 trillion).
Legislators thus ignored President George Bush’s request to support the plan.
In Bush’s view, the plan would settle the root causes of the financial crisis and thus help stabilize the entire economy.
American stocks experienced a massacre on Monday, and the major stock indices recorded the largest slump in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones Index declined by almost 7%, a similar decline it had last recorded in 1987.
The index had already fallen before the vote, but there was little evidence that the draft would not get through in the House of Representatives, the index experienced a free fall.
Congress concedes: U.S. government is allowed to pump $700 billion into banks
The top representatives of the U.S. Congress and the government of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of an agreement to provide financial assistance to the U.S. financial system.
This will be voted on early next week.
U.S. lawmakers made a breakthrough in talks about the adoption of a rescue plan in the form of financial assistance to the U.S. financial system in the amount of $700 billion (about 12 trillion crowns).
However, this does not mean a victory.
Congressmen still have to negotiate some details of the agreement before they can publish the final version of the law and vote on it.
The plan to support the financial system will be negotiated in the U.S. Congress on Monday.
On Sunday, the chairman of the Banking and Financial Services Committee, Barney Frank, told Reuters.
The Senate could vote on the plan at the earliest on Wednesday, according to different reports.
According to economists, a communication on the adoption of the plan should be the first significant psychological factor in revitalizing financial markets.
After that, however, there is a "disappointment" due to the complicated mechanisms, how the markets could also be helped in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We have made significant progress.
We have clarified our different views on what a market stabilization package should look like,” said Nancy Pelosi, a Democrat.
According to her, there could be a final vote on Sunday.
Representatives of the legislature met with U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson the night after Sunday to give the government fund its final form.
This envisages a buy-off of unpurchased mortgage assets from the financial companies, which plunge financial firms into heavy losses and endanger the stability of the entire system.
“We are on the verge of a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and must be effective in the market.
We need to continue the recovery plan, but I think we’re at the goal,” Paulson said.
A signal for Asian business
The global financial crisis is also clearly reflected in the stock markets, which are declining sharply.
According to Nevada Democratic Senator Harry Reid, lawmakers are trying to reach a final agreement in Congress before Sunday.
This is intended to reassure investors of transactions in the Asian financial markets, which are in the first time zone, where a decision by Congress could affect business on Monday.
So far, however, it is not entirely clear when both chambers of the American Congress will vote on the law, and there is also uncertainty as to whether the negotiations could fail at the last minute on a problem.
Legislators hope it will be passed in the next few days.
But the law will have some changes.
The total amount allocated to assist the system shall be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion is to be provided as soon as possible, as President George Bush demanded.
Congress, however, can block the distribution of the remaining money if it has the impression that the program is not fulfilling its function, at another $100 billion and later the final $350 billion.
Bush welcomes progress in negotiation
The president has the right to veto this decision, but Congress can override his veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program has persisted, which was based on obtaining finance for the purchase of bad mortgage securities whose value has fallen because hundreds of thousands of Americans are no longer able to repay their mortgages.
“We’ve worked out everything.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the law on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday,” said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
The US President Bush was also pleased with the progress.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, said Bush was satisfied with Saturday’s progress and “appreciated the mutual effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy.”
Restriction of golden parachutes
Senate banking committee chairman Christopher Dodd, the senior negotiator, said lawmakers had agreed on a responsibility for the money program, protecting taxpayers from losses, closing benefits, and a schedule for funding the plan.
The new law is also intended to limit the so-called golden parachutes for directors of companies involved in the program and establish a committee to supervise the fund.
The Ministry of Finance will lead it.
“We have worked very hard and made great progress towards an agreement that works and is important for the market and for all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also anticipates help for homeowners who have trouble repaying their mortgage.
The government should negotiate new installments on mortgages that it buys up, with the goal of reducing the monthly costs for debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
According to Patria Finance’s chief economist David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but implementation will be very difficult.
“That’s because you don’t know by what mechanism and at what price the problematic assets are bought.
This will be crucial for how the financial sector and the government divide the losses among themselves,” Marek told the server iHNed.cz this week.
Whether the plan will be adopted now or at the beginning of next week is not crucial in Marek’s view.
“It is much more important that Congressmen agree to support the plan and that they say goodbye to it as soon as possible.
The psychological importance of the agreement on a passing is the most important thing at this moment,” Marek stressed.
Duel on Messer's cutting edge: MP3 player against mobile phones.
We advise you on your choice
While almost every mobile phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make phone calls yet.
So, of course, it looks better to just buy a phone.
However, there are plenty of reasons why you should get an independent player.
The choice depends entirely on the type of use and the claims of the future owner.
It’s hard to buy an expensive record player at home to listen to Maxim Turbulenc’s latest album.
Once such musical novelties do not appear on LPs, and from a qualitative point of view there is no objective reason for this.
However, if you have LPs with art rock, jazz or blues on the shelf, you probably dream of at least one.
This is how it is simplified with music when traveling, i.e. with compressed music - music in MP3 format.
Here, too, there are price and quality categories.
For one, it may not be acceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, but a Pink Floyd fan will probably not be able to handle headphones for twenty crowns from the market.
Two extremes, between which there is enough space for everyone.
The selection is wide.
The battery life is also crucial.
Some good music players can play much more than just music, but what mobile phones can do, they don’t even create indicatively.
No modern device is as universal as the phone.
In addition to the primary functions, the phone and the sims, it can play music and videos, record both, it sometimes has a better, sometimes a worse camera and may also be able to navigate.
And if you include the smartphones and communicators, you have almost a small computer in your pocket.
It’s a little wonder, because no refrigerator can grill and no TV can photograph.
But the universality of the mobile phones also brings disadvantages.
However, the more features you use on your phone, the more often you will need to reload it.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy eaters.
Few mobile phones can play music for longer than ten to twelve hours, usually it is much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
That’s why you should expect the cheap phones to be able to play music for no more than a few hours.
If you still call from time to time, you would rather buy a charger for the office for safety - this also applies to more expensive devices.
With MP3 players, you won’t have this problem, even the less good ones will endure at least 9 hours of uninterrupted operation at once.
Another problem is if you want to transfer the music to your mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a small part of the devices have a USB port, and not every mobile phone can be connected directly to a PC without special software.
Of course, you can transfer the music directly to a storage medium, but only a few card readers are done without reduction with the tiny memory cards that are used in mobile phones.
For players, you do not need any special software except for exceptions (iPod).
You only need to feed the device with music from your PC via USB port.
Most mobile phones and players themselves create a music library, ordered by the name of the performer, the title of the album, the genre or, for example, the evaluation by users.
Some devices only map the tree structure of the address directory, similar to Windows Explorer, some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Players are easier to use, mobile phones can do more
When choosing a specific device, you should inquire about the battery life, storage capacity, quality and type of sound and, of course, ease of use.
If music is the backdrop for you and you listen to it every day only briefly, for example in the tram, then any mobile phone that plays MP3 files is enough.
What almost every cell phone can do.
You also do not have to control which music formats a mobile phone or a player can process.
MP3 creates all, and most of the music you get will just be in this format.
The format is one of the most common, and most devices can also play music in WMA format.
Less common is AAC (a format that Apple and its iPods use).
Better mobile phones also make it possible to buy music online.
You only need to access the corresponding pages of a provider (or another provider) via mobile internet, and you can now buy a song or album.
This service can in itself be a striking argument for why you should buy a music cell phone.
Unfortunately, the offer of the providers is poor and is mostly limited to fast radio hits.
The prices are not the lowest either.
In general, however, it is assumed that this type of music sales (whether via GSM, Internet or wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry the phone with them.
If you feel like listening to something, grab the phone in your pocket while the player is lying forgotten at home.
However, it depends on whether you also carry headphones or at least a wireless hands-free device.
If not, you can rely on the built-in speaker that almost every mobile phone has, but only the fewest MP3 players.
Probably the biggest advantage of the music mobile phones will be in price for many.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand crowns.
For three and four thousand crowns you already get a decent Walkman.
The biggest handicap for most will be that no normal headphones are included.
The best and most technically sophisticated phones with a 3.5mm opening for regular headphones cost up to fifteen thousand crowns.
The advantage of the players in turn lies in the easy operation.
The simplest - and not necessarily cheapest (see selection) - players can really serve anyone.
A minimum of functions, the similarity in operation with the formerly normal cassette recorder or, for example, the turntable, is obvious.
There is no threat of collision in the form of an erroneously employed mobile internet and a subsequently horrifying invoice for data transmissions.
What device should you reach now
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable storage media (type M2, microSD, etc.).
Even if you buy a card, two thousand crowns are enough.
But be careful.
