Be one of the more demanding listeners, take specialized phones - Walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some from Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have stand-alone control buttons for MP3, and the ease of use comes close to that of a single MP3 player.
The furthest here is Sony Ericsson, whose phones from the Walkman series have the same user interface as the individually sold MP3 players.
The same services in the same price category of up to four thousand crowns, but with a higher storage capacity (up to 16 GB) and a long battery life (usually 15 hours, maximum up to 35 hours) will provide you with MP3 players from the above-mentioned manufacturers.
The first virtual provider is coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Probably
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech providers offer practically all services, as are also offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classics at lower prices.
Maybe he won’t wait long.
We have often reported on Mobil.cz that the Czech mobile carriers are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was also confirmed by the telecommunications authority T, which pointed out that the price of an SMS is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
After the last steps taken by the European Commission in the area of regulation of roaming fees, there is so likely to be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile carriers, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
Why are the prices in the Czech Republic so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks the competition that really makes a fight statement.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, because in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
The mobile operators, on the other hand, like to scold the fact that there is extremely much competition in the Czech market.
This is often also supported by the Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunication Authority (CTA) Pavel Dvorák, who in the past had often stated that there was no room for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classic provider with its own network no longer has a lot of chances (by the way, he would probably hardly find frequencies).
But there is another possibility – a virtual provider.
Particularly the entry of virtual providers into the mobile market resulted in a significant price reduction, to which the classic mobile providers also had to respond.
Before such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the UK market, there were voices similar to those in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
By the way, you don’t have to look for examples for long.
In February we reported on the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to attract more than 100 thousand customers and thus become the fifth largest provider in the country.
Behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual providers is that you can focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need far fewer customers than a classic provider.
They do not require relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually stand out as low-cost companies - they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers SMS in the UK at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good move to bet on a non-cliché target group.
This provider is specifically aimed at men.
“Real guys choose Mobilking – the provider they like and trust,” said David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, the operating company of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could take root in the Czech Republic.
Vodafone Miroslav’s spokesperson for the press said: “The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of service provision."
In the Czech Republic, mobile operators mean
However, it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile carrier conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be Mobilking.
“While we are talking about an expansion of this successful project, the negotiations in the Czech Republic are not particularly hopeful.
Mobilking will be more likely to enter the market in other countries in our region," said Jana Studniá, a spokeswoman for the Penta financial group.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything to ensure that no potential competitor emerges.
For some time now, the GTS Novera Group has shown its interest in launching a virtual mobile service provider, which wants to take another step in becoming a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
“We have a great interest in providing our customers with not only fixed-line, but also mobile telecommunication services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile carriers.
With some of them, we have already been able to achieve negotiation progress," said group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
Maybe there are better times now.
Unofficial information indicates that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
To date, however, this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
“At this moment, we don’t expect there to be room for a full-fledged virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
No subject has yet addressed us with a complex and reputable project in this area," said Vlastimil Sr.e. from the Telefónica O2 press department in his statement to Mobil.cz.
Other providers also point to the specifics of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová adds in rare agreement with O2’s statement: “So far, we have not found a viable and mutually beneficial project to continue on.”
And she adds: “T-Mobile’s network will hardly see a virtual provider by the end of the year.
At this moment, we would have to have a concrete offer to be able to think in such a short time.”
Vodafone focuses more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
“We are open to negotiating with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of cost and infrastructure sharing.
This is exactly what we see as the best from the customer’s point of view.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile internet.”
The responsible authorities - hand in hand with the providers
The actions of the mobile operators are easy to understand, another provider would be more competition, this would lead to falling prices and thus also to a decline in profits.
So why make it easier for such a competitor to enter the market?
The fact that the providers can pull together when it comes to something also proves the long back and forth about the emergence of U:fon.
Probably the strongest pressure in the direction of ‘T’ came from the company T-Mobile at the time when U:fon came on the market.
This is also evidenced by the publicly available information from the T websites.
Now, however, U:fon is suitable as an argument why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová commented: “The competitive environment of the mobile market has also recently been strengthened by the entry of a fourth mobile service provider.
Taking into account the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and, above all, its services."
Given this approach, however, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is surprising.
It is not just the attitude of the T, which unfortunately, unlike the UK and other highly developed countries, does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
It is owned exclusively by the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (OHS).
This, however, involved his typical attitude to this whole problem.
“The entry into the market of a virtual mobile carrier would be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile carrier and a virtual carrier for renting the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, because the offer of potential prospects was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classic providers," said Kristián Chalupa of the External Relations Department of the .OHS in his reply to our question.
From representatives of the providers would not surprise such a wording.
This is more than a concern of an authority that represents consumer interests and, among other things, is to ensure that no one abuses their position on the market.
Particularly when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Above all, abroad, where virtual providers work normally, it is to be observed that their entry into the market has contributed to a price reduction in mobile telephone services."
However, the pressure on the correct functioning of the market and a price reduction probably do not belong to the interests of the OHS.
Really shocking in this case is the almost already touching harmony of the three mobile carriers, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the absolutely same gasoline price at the gas stations is certainly just a coincidence and the result of a tough competition.
"The Authority has not discovered any indications of anti-competitive action in this matter and therefore has no reason to intervene in the matter in any way.
None of the providers has a dominant market position, so they do not have the corresponding increased responsibility for their actions in the market.
The necessary tools for opening up the mobile market to virtual providers are probably also lacking in the telecommunications regulator,” Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, elaborated by the “T”, after which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile carriers have a dominant position.
Some legal experts, however, offer a different view - for a virtual provider to enter the market, the consent of the network operator is always necessary.
And, logically, the mobile provider has the monopoly for its network.
This means that it necessarily occupies a dominant position in a particular segment.
But even if you don’t agree with this argument, it should be at least a warning for the OHS that three mobile carriers are strikingly similar.
Complaints from a number of interested parties (including GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles when negotiating with all providers.
The diversion of responsibility to the T is then a fairly common trick in telecommunications services, with which the OHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act did not succeed in enforcing the extension of the competences of the T to the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the OHS have to know this all too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's okay when no one is looking
First of all, the functioning of any pseudovirtual providers, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
They are companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but they are only partially public.
Usually, these are companies that operate in the field of multilevel marketing.
Own mobile telephone services offer, for example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the chosen ones.
The joke of the matter is that the company appears to the operator as a classic corporate customer who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile carriers prohibit similar resale.
"If there are cases that you describe, it may be a violation of the contractual terms, which we will then deal with, which may lead to an end to the cooperation with the appropriate company," Martina Kemrová replied to our question on this issue.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing does not go around with the managers of the mobile providers.
Particularly in the case of the three companies mentioned, they can be thousands of customers.
However, no operator is opposed to such an approach.
The profits from the activities of these companies are not negligible, but at the same time, unlike the actual virtual providers, they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav points out that there may be problems: "The law allows for such speculation, despite the fact that the services of these companies are only used by a very small percentage of customers.
They also have to accept that the SIM card in their phone is not running on their name, so they can’t have full access to it like the normal customers of the mobile carriers.”
But that alone should at least be strange.
There is also another question for the OHS.
The mobile operators are closing their eyes before such action, why are they blocking themselves against a virtual provider?
It should be added that the OHS has quite strong competencies for detecting such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the statement made by the providers that they do not know about it and their terms and conditions would prohibit it.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has already been emphasized several times in the text, the market entry of virtual providers brought with it a significant price decrease in the various services.
In practically all countries where virtual providers have emerged, the classic providers have tried to prevent their emergence more or less.
The arguments they used were practically identical - a market too small or too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, the regulatory authorities intervened at these moments, which did not try to protect the interests of the mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Whether through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they managed to create the first virtual operator, and more followed.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are throwing up the whole case like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that ambiguity in competences is more than favorable in these cases.
But let's not throw the gun in the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider soon emerges, the Czech mobile market may be set to move again soon.
If a provider allows the emergence of a virtual mobile carrier, the OHS will not remain idle when it comes to rejecting (discriminating) other prospects.
And the Czechs will finally not be more expensive than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Find the best
Listen to the four versions of the new Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, on the occasion of the Day of the Czech Statehood, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek presented the new recordings of the national anthem Where Is My Homeland.
The anthem was re-recorded by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jia Bulhohlávek.
There are four versions available - with male or female solo vocals, in choral version and in an instrumental version.
The song was written by Kateina Knánková and Adam Plachetka.
The editors of the hymn versions are Otakar Jeremi’ and Jaroslav Krácek.
On the server iHNed.cz you can listen to all four versions.
The Czech national anthem is one of the most beautiful hymns for Bolohlávek.
Earlier, he had told the Czech Radio that he had chosen singers with young, representative voices for the solo variants, which are striking and popular.
"From the very beginning, I have tried to keep a clear diction with both and then with the choir, so that the text is well understood, so that a harmony is created," says the conductor.
The Czech National Anthem celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Kde domov máj first sounded in 1834 on the stage of the stall theatre in the originally Czech piece Fidlovaácka by Josef Kajetán Tyl, the music came from Franti’ek Ekroup.
It became popular, and people took it spontaneously.
The first verse of the song then became an organic part of the national anthem after the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918.
It remained one of the seven state symbols even after the emergence of the independent Czech Republic.
