The Prague transport companies are also transporting on a chip for the first time on Wednesday
Wednesday, October 1, 2008, will go down in the history of Prague's transport operations as a date when the first passengers to board a subway, tram or bus will be able to carry an electronic coupon in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
Currently, about one hundred thousand people can buy them, who have the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy a 30-day, a 90-day or an annual coupon (valid from 1 January 2009) and can play it on their chip card at the information centers and branch offices of the transport companies at the metro stations Muzeum, Mástek, Nádrac Holecovice, Andal, Roztyer, Kazary, Kazary, and Kozany.
Since yesterday, the coupons are also available via the Internet on the pages of the transport companies www.dpp.cz.
The service was used until the afternoon by more than four hundred customers.
Those who use the internet sale can really forget the output window in the subway stations, where they had to wait regularly in long lines for their paper tickets.
You buy the coupon via the Internet, which is displayed on the Opencard in one of the thirteen branches of the city library.
"At these places, travelers also have a desk with trained staff available, which advises interested parties on buying the internet and also puts the coupon on the card," says project spokesman Martin Opatrn.
In addition to the libraries, you can also add the electronic coupons to the open card at self-service machines, which are attached in some subway vessels.
What do these machines look like?
They are red, remind of ticket scorers, the passengers may have already noticed them at the metro stations Roztyly, Budjovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
“There are currently five of them in the city, but by the end of the year it should be eighty,” Opatrná adds.
A machine controls the coupon instead of the driver
The operation of the vending machines, which will work from tomorrow, is easy.
You just have to introduce the chip card, and the previously purchased coupon will appear on its own.
The electronic coupons will apply from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the surrounding area.
So in the suburban trains and on the bus lines with the numbers 300 to 499, with which mainly the inhabitants of the municipalities of the region Central Bohemia get to the capital.
"In the trains that are part of Prague's integrated transport system, the train attendants have readers with which they can check the validity of the coupons by time and zone," explains Filip Drápal from the organisation Ropid, who compiles the timetables for the Prague transport companies.
The suburban buses have card readers at the driver's checkout.
When boarding, the chip card must not only be shown to the driver, but the open card must be placed at a marked point on the side of the checkout.
In this way, the driver checks the validity of the coupons.
"For a passenger to check the validity of the coupons, nothing is easier than to ask the driver for this information," Drápal said.
A passenger who does not travel on suburban buses and no longer knows when the validity of the coupon ends can in turn go to the self-service vending machines, where the coupons are deposited on the card.
Here the information about the validity of its documents is displayed on the display of the device.
The Sudeten demanded a referendum from the United States
The Sudeten Germans had requested the annexation of the Bohemian Forest to the United States in 1945.
This is evident from a letter that is stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, at least we want to live under the auspices of the United States of America.
With such a wish, in 1945 some groups of Sudeten Germans turned to the US president.
Among other things, this is evident from a letter that has been preserved in a private archive and is now kept in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
The Germans of Krumau in the letter ask the American president not to allow the return of the "Sudetengau" - which was taken by Hitler on the basis of the Munich Agreement - to Czechoslovakia.
“We have understood the situation correctly and really want to be sure of the words that the American units are not entering German territory as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators,” the letter reads.
Since the connection to Czechoslovakia suggests that the Sudeten Germans - in knowledge of the Czech national character - would expect brutality, recklessness, lack of understanding, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American President to take over the protection of the Bohemian Forest for today and forever.
“We cannot believe that, regardless of the view of a quarter of a million inhabitants, you are addressing this area to a state that is foreign to us, which oppresses and tries to eliminate minorities, and has contributed nothing at all to the victory of the Allies,” the letter reads.
The reason why the authors can’t sign is allegedly the fear of vengeance from the “Czech oppressors”.
If the US president has doubts about the attitude of the Bohemian Forest Germans, it would be sufficient if he initiated a referendum in the Bohemian Forestgau on whether the inhabitants would become part of the USA or live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text of the letter may sound somewhat naive in today’s knowledge of post-war history, according to some contemporary witnesses, it draws a good picture of the expectations of the Sudeten Germans at that time.
Even though the Bohemian Germans had to at least suspect that they would be negotiated on their deportation from the republic, few of them even admitted such a possibility.
Some waited for the United States and Britain to negotiate some sort of autonomy for the Sudetes.
Others thought they could just stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is also confirmed by the famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, who is from Budweis.
He was employed in the war as a Budweiser German in the navy on the Baltic Sea.
When he came into British captivity at the end of the war and was taken to a prisoner-of-war camp in Holstein, dozens of other Bohemian Germans came to him to teach them Czech.
“They believed that if they came home, the Czech would suit them,” Chalupa said.
None of the German prisoners of war who had lived in Czechoslovakia before the war, in his opinion, expected him to be expelled from the Republic on the basis of the Benei decrees.
