Even rats have feelings.
A rat or a cockroach flees in danger, does it also feel fear?
Neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that many animals also have feelings.
Only how can you check if they feel the same way when they behave similarly to us?
In the internet magazine "Edge", contributions of famous scientists have been published for several years.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series selected answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else ever being able to prove this where we can’t even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope, since all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as soon as we turn to other species and raise questions of feeling or, more generally, of consciousness, we enter impassable terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same as many other animals: it stands dead, flees or attacks.
People behave similarly, which is why some scientists suggest a similar subjective experience.
However, I do not believe in that.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
On the one hand, the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the lateral prefrontal cortex (because of its involvement in short-term memory and in execution/control functions).
This broad region is much more developed in humans than in the other primates and seems to be completely lacking in other creatures.
So, at least on those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including knowing who we are and the ability to plan and decide, there is reason to believe that man is even different from the other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity may lie in the linguistic nature of man: Since such a large part of his experience is associated with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness does not depend on language, it would certainly affect it, so that animal consciousness, whatever its nature, is probably very different from most of our states of consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness may look like in other animals.
If, as something internal and subjective, it can neither be measured nor, because of the special hardware, analyzed on the basis of our own experience, his research presents us with great problems.
Most of my remarks relate to the content of conscious experience, but there is also another aspect of consciousness that is likely to be more scientifically accessible.
One could study the consciousness processes of animals without regard to their contents, and that is exactly what happens in studies on the short-term memory of primates, especially the example of visualization.
But this approach, which Christof Koch and Francis Crick followed, focuses more on the neural correlates of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: both may or may not be identical.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex for the emergence of visualization.
What is the result for the sensations?
I draw them back to the fact that an emotional system like that of fear is activated in a brain conscious of its own activity.
So what we call “fear” is the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) occupies memory.
In this way, sensations are closely linked to the regions of the cortex that distinguish primates and, in particular, humans.
Connected with linguistic nature, there are fine gradations of feeling, because we can differentiate and categorize states with the help of words and grammar, in order to attribute them to others besides ourselves.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that sensations from more primitive activities in the body-sensing regions of the cortex and brainstem are similar to Jaak Pankseep, which, however, focuses more on the brainstem.
Since this network has not changed very much in the course of human evolution, it could well be involved in cross-generational sensations.
In theory, I cannot disagree with this, but I think it is unprovable.
Pankseep argues that what appears to be like fear in rats and people probably feels like this in both cases: but how can you check whether rats and people feel the same when they behave similarly?
A cockroach flees in danger if it also feels fear?
In my opinion, mere behavioral similarity cannot yet prove equality of experience.
Although the neural comparison further helps: rats and humans have similar brain stems, on the other hand, not even a brain.
But is the brain stem responsible for sensations?
And even if you could prove it to humans, how would you prove it to rats?
I believe that rats and other mammals, perhaps even cockroaches (who knows?), have sensations.
But I don't know how to prove it.
And because their feelings are probably fundamentally different from ours (because human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I prefer to explore the emotional behavior rather than the emotional sensations of rats.
In any case, progress is waving at the neural level, if you measure the same in rats and humans.
As I don’t explore language and consciousness in rats, nor sensations, I don’t know if they exist.
You might think of it as short-sighted, but I'd rather move forward than run against a wall all the time.
I am a practical emotionalist.
