In this edition of the "Education Watch", Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the positions of the candidates for bilingual training.
Lance T. Izumi, senior researcher in Caliphonic Studies and senior director in the Department of Education at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is a co-author of the book "Not as good as you think: Why the middle class needs a school selection".
Addressing Hispanic voters is a complicated task.
Barack Obama’s proposals on education are a typical example of this.
Obama’s election campaign mentions that “the likelihood of African-American and Hispanic students successfully completing school is lower than that of white students” – which is true.
To close this gap, Obama’s education plan specifically recommends a bilingual transitional period in education for those who are just learning English.
Still, the question for Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which focuses on teaching in languages other than English, contradicts his interest in reducing the gap in school performance.
Take, for example, "Sixth Street Prep", a primary school in eastern Los Angeles.
The majority of students are Hispanic and come from low-income families.
More than a third of the students, many of whom have only recently been in the country, learn English.
Still, in 2008, an astonishing 100 percent of fourth-grade students passed the state exam in math at a good level.
Also surprisingly, 93 percent of children from the fourth year of school were rated as good in the English exam.
This astonishing success has been achieved using methods other than those favored by Obama.
The Sixth Street School focuses on review and practice, on constant control of knowledge and an attitude that tolerates no exceptions.
Furthermore, the school practices the approach that education takes in an English-speaking environment, which is exactly what Obama should consider, according to school principal Linda Mikels.
This approach emphasizes the almost exclusive use of the English language in specialist classes.
Ms. Mikels, who rejects the idea of bilingual education, told me that the school had a remarkable success with a student who had just come from Mexico. Twelve months later, one would be able to enter the classroom and not recognize him.
