The pride and hardship in the life of the black population, in a city of a very special kind
Hidden among the sprawlings of the amusement parks around Orlando, a few miles from the glittering, noisy and gigantic hustle and bustle, lies a quiet city where the pride and complications of African American culture emerge.
Eatonville, the first wholly black city in the country and hometown of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as easy to describe as Hurston did in 1935: "the city with 5 lakes, three crocket courts, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, more than enough guavas, 2 schools and no prison."
Today it is a pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! festival in Eatonville to commemorate the most famous author of the Harlem Renaissance.
And yet the city that describes it – and which made it a tourist destination by introducing it to the Florida Travel Guide, which was produced by the federal writers’ project during the time of the depression – is and remains, in many ways, a very special place.
Eatonville is as independent, sophisticated and private as it was in the 1930s when Hurston wrote that rural black communities in Florida often refused to share their true thoughts with the white man who “knows so little about us that he doesn’t know what he misses.”
Even nowadays, in a year when a black presidential candidacy is calling for Senator Barack Obama to talk openly about race relations, many here are still tired of being watched by outsiders.
“We are very attentive to how our story is told,” said Hortense Jones, 59, from birth to a resident of the city and a community member of the city’s oldest church.
It has to be true.”
Eatonville has long been defined as the paradox of triumph and struggle.
It is both a historical example of the black movement and a community of almost 2,400 inhabitants, where the poverty rate is twice as high as the national average.
It is, on the one hand, a stronghold of literature and, on the other hand, an example of the - sometimes condemned, sometimes praised - black culture of the rural South, which has its roots in American slavery.
Not surprisingly, residents here are both proud and watchful.
And so the concerns about Eatonville's image actually started with Zora, as everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced her hometown to the world in books that came from the heart and were written in dialect, such as "Mules and Men" (1953) and "Their Eyes were watching God" (1973)
Five paragraphs in the Florida guide changed the city, which is very close to Route 77, a road that leads through the often-forgotten center of Florida, to the scenes of black history and human drama.
Cheeky like Oskar in both real life and literature, Hurston led readers to the store of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then turned to more private matters.
"Away from the road to the left," she wrote, "is the brown-white-painted modern school, with its well-groomed gardens and playgrounds that Howard Miller always cares about, though he can barely read and write."
She also mentioned the new husband of Widow Dash and wrote that Lee Glenn “sells drinks of any kind and what-always fits in with classrooms.”
In just a few hundred words, Hurston associated Eatonville with self-government, but also with illiteracy, second marriage, and sex.
This was certainly not a travel guide.
In fact, this was not a portrait that was appreciated by everyone.
“Zora described things the way they were,” said Ella Dinkins, 90, one of the Johnson girls who immortalized Hurston by quoting the men who sang songs about her beauty, which were full of sexual allusions.
She added, “Some people didn’t like this.”
Hurtson is still remembered here as a lively eccentric who returned regularly after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalled that when Hurston came to town, she usually did so without warning, in a noisy Chevrolet, smoking and dressed in pants, in a city that even today imagines something of her venerable style of dress.
According to Mr. Franklin, most residents were fascinated, while many despised them.
“People were always glad to see Zora,” said Mr. Franklin.
But “she never stayed too long,” he added as he rocked in his chair, on a back-facing terrace overlooking the Sabelia Lake, where Hurston was most likely baptized.
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of stock.
Along with most of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten them.
Although she was once a famous author, a contemporary Langstin Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an anonymous grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she lived.
In Eatonville there was no great memorial, no public readings in large style.
“I don’t think they understood their contribution to the world or their legacy at all,” says Valerie Boyd, author of “Wrapped in Rainbows,” a biography about Hurston published in 2003.
The turnaround came in the 80s.
Orange County authorities wanted to lay a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the town's slow two-lane main road.
Orlando’s suburbs had already pushed Highway 4 through the western outskirts of the city.
The proposal was made when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the fight against racial mixing brought hatred to the community.
“At that time, a bunch of white boys often came and they threw oranges and stuff at the secluded people,” Mr. Franklin said.
“There was even a woman who was killed.
They threw a watermelon out of the car.”
In 1955, Hurston, in a letter to the Orlando Sentinel, questioned the Supreme Court’s demand to force integration by calling Brown’s decision against the school council “offensive rather than respectful of my race.”
Residents today say that although the abolition of racial segregation was positive in some respects, it weakened group cohesion in Eatonville and the self-confidence of its youth.
“Black children were used to being hugged – I remember – one hugged his teacher in the morning and one hugged his teacher in the evening,” said N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and executive director of the nonprofit group for the protection of the Eatonville community.
This could be maintained, she added, until teachers and students no longer came from the same place.
"You didn't hug his white teacher because he was a white teacher - I mean there's a cultural divide," Mrs. Nathiri said.
However, civil rights have helped create space for more Zora Neale Hurston's -- black writers, actors, and artists who disregarded prejudice, as she did, with positive self-confidence and statements like, "How can anyone deny the joy of my society!
I don't understand."
In 1975, writer Alice Walker set out for Hurston's nameless tomb and began fighting for the revival of her fame.
Five years later, a much acclaimed Hurston biography of Robert E. Hemenway was found on the bookshelves, and again made it a part of the American literary canon.
The highway project came at a time when Eatonville’s most famous daughter once again stood in the public light.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The municipality began planning a Hurston Festival in 1988 to show what the district could destroy with the construction of the highway.
Thousands of fans came to the opening event two years later, and every January many return for the celebration.
A few years later, the district turned away from its road construction plans.
"The plans of a five-lane highway revived the city, accelerated the whole thing at peak speed, aroused real public pride," said Ms. Nathiri.
Ms. Boyd put it a little easier: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory against the highway project has contributed to a change in the city’s self-image.
There were more and more concierges, such as Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who has been going to church here since 1993, and locals began to reappreciate the past.
Eatonville was included in the nationwide historical register in 1998.
A new one-storey library (of course named after Hurston) opened in 2006 on the newly paved and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a peculiarity in Florida: only 6 miles from Orlando city centre, it can sometimes feel like a back road in the summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded by only 27 black families in the 1880s.
(It's 90% black nowadays.)
Outsiders in search of the history of Eatonville and its significance are often still treated with caution.
For most interviews, permission is required in advance and certain things – such as the wall painting of Eatonville’s oldest church, painted by a white man and depicting black men in the field work – may not be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, such as Ms. Jones, a courageous, confident teacher with a penchant for dark red, still fear that her shielded community will be misunderstood.
And yet, at the same time that the Hurston Festival got bigger, an increased degree of homeland pride was also born.
Especially young people tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw their entire race: beautiful, with all its problems, neither worse nor better and as proud, creative and diligent, silly and mixed up as any other racial and ethnic group in America.
It is the sincere love for this city that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin’s nephew, the 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the city administration or the police, who could use some help, according to him.
And even the younger ones, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, eleven-year-old twins from Winter Park, have learned to correctly describe Eatonville.
“Most of the people who drive through here will think, ‘Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others,” Alondra Kenon said on a Sunday after the church.
“But if you actually stop and look at its history for a moment, it’s a very beautiful city.”
