According to statistics, between 30-75% of drivers who were reported more than once because of driving under the influence of alcohol again sat at the wheel.
The 'alcolock' would prevent this because it is a system connected to the car, it measures the alcohol content in the exhaled air and prevents autostart when the driver has done alcohol test; or if an alcohol concentration is detected that is higher than allowed.
It costs more than 1 000 euros, the costs are borne by the person who imposes the penalty.
In this context, a study conducted in the U.S. in 2007 showed that cars equipped with these devices prevent up to 65% of rule violations in the first year after its introduction.
In Spain, it is estimated that 115 lives could be saved each year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to tackle this behavior before it becomes a criminal offence.
And to facilitate their implementation, a legal reform can be implemented by the ordinary way, and yet a reform of the Basic Law is required, which is necessary for the law enforcement process.
Still, the device is available in the Spanish markets, in no store, although it has already been installed in some commercial vehicles and public transport vehicles.
The House of Representatives will vote tomorrow on the initiative of the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party, which is proposing to install this system in school buses, as has already been done in France.
