Conversation - The Blood That Has Been Safe Again
Hema-Quebec celebrated its 10th anniversary yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, for Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, it has regained the public's confidence, which had been severely shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
It is known that the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross’s blood donation service during the 1980s were contaminated with the HI virus and the hepatitis C virus.
In the face of this drama and public dissatisfaction, in February 1994, the Government of Canada initiated a public investigation, led by Judge Horace Krever, aimed to shed light on the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy, and to draw up guidelines to prevent a further disaster of this kind.
While Judge Krever was still hesitant to report, several provinces set up a committee to develop a new system for managing canned blood in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee carried out this task.
According to reports by Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Society to provide for the other provinces and the two territories.
In 1998, when Hema-Quebec began its work, barely 38% of people had confidence in the blood-conserving system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
Through the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood canned people and through the work in this field over the following years, we have regained the public’s confidence,’ she says, before proudly stressing that by the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of the population had Quebec’s confidence in Hema-Quebec.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps in mind that “trust is something extremely fragile.”
Since its inception on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has been acting according to the principle of caution.
At that time, we witnessed the appearance of numerous cases of the human form of bovine madness in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says this woman, who has been in charge since its inception in 1998.
"And we had no idea if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
So we referred to one of the main guidelines of Krever and Gélineau’s reports, which states that exclusion measures are applied if one does not know this and if a disease progresses only slowly, as is evidently the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which manifests itself as a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
Thus, in April 1999, no blood was taken from people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Now, a few years ago, there was no doubt that this disease was transmitted through the blood.
Thus, this event has shown us that the principle of caution that we applied does make sense.
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NST), which allow the presence of the virus itself directly in the donor’s blood, and not that of the antibodies against the virus, as was the case with the tests used so far.
The NST made it possible to shorten the incubation time that takes place between when the person was infected and when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to less than a week.
Thus, the risk that certain donors might be infected without knowing it, and one could not detect it, was significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmitting AIDS via a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
“In other words, it means distributing 12 million canned blood before someone gets infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 canned blood each year, it would take more than 24 years for a case of HIV to be transmitted via a canned bloodstream.
I believe that these days you can feel comfortable when you get a blood transfusion or prescribe it to restore health," says Hema-Quebec's chief executive.
“Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen can enter the system.
Just last year, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by insects through the blood.
We need to continuously monitor,” Dr. Décary continues, before stressing that Hema-Quebec must provide adequate care in addition to safe care.
“The demand is increasing as the population ages.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also affects the blood-donor network, which on average only includes 3% of Quebec’s blood-donor population.”
Every healthy person who is 18 years or older and meets the aptitude criteria can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who provide their blood are not accepted because they have, for example, AIDS or malaria, and those who have traveled to a country where malaria is widespread are excluded from blood donation for one year.
“With these 3%, we manage to get an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Lack of supplies is very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network as they get older and can no longer donate blood.
It’s hard to convince people to donate blood, but most importantly, to keep them and get them to become regular donors.
Life is so hectic these days that you rarely find the time to spend an hour donating blood,” says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec provides not only blood but also human tissue, including bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin, which is used almost exclusively in severe fire injuries.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before interim storage at Hema-Quebec, which also manages Quebec’s only public cord blood bank.
The umbilical cord, formerly considered biomedical waste, contains blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“A few weeks ago we celebrated the storage of our thousandth umbilical cord blood sample, and we plan to lose more than a thousand annually.
"We should probably start making it available for transplants at the beginning of next year," Dr. Décary continues, who describes this program of umbilical cord blood loss as very popular.
“Many mothers are convinced they don’t have access to it because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and costly program in all Quebec hospitals.
