The Psychology of Overbidding – or Why We Are Ready to Pay More
In auctions, buyers tend to spend more and overestimate what is offered.
Neurologists and economic researchers at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic foundations of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in Science magazine, people do not want to be beaten in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even excessive prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers should play lottery, while the other participated in a playful action - in both cases, the subjects' active brain regions were examined using functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games, the participants were able to win money, but increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the brain cord, was measured in the case of auction losers, in which the overbidding of the opponent plays an essential role.
Among many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-rewarding" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore thought that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the striatum.
To support their thesis, the economists in the research group have also conducted research to track the money.
In this case, three groups should compete against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their bets.
Another group was also promised $15 reward, in case they emerge from the game as winners.
The third group received $15 before the auction, which were also lost in case of a lost game.
So the difference between the two groups was that the emphasis on one was on winning, while the other was on losing.
As evidence of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, however, the members of the "against losing" group were willing to engage higher than those in the control or "win" group.
"These findings cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
These have so far only justified the behaviors observed at auctions with the joy of winning or avoiding risk.
The contradiction between these two theories has been resolved thanks to imaging neurological procedures, so we now have a third explanation ready," said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When to see the doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people is estimated to be one hundred thousand in this country, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ from each other.
Depending on the pathogen, the hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in the case of hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example, through contaminated food or water), in the case of hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other body fluids (such as sperm, vaginal secretion or saliva).
Travelers are recommended to be vaccinated against viruses A and B, and there is no vaccine against virus C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear about two to three weeks after consumption of the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that, jaundice occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the stool becomes bright, the urine dark, and the recovery can last up to two-three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die each year from hepatitis B-induced, far more serious diseases such as liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten infected people is in medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, as the pathogen insidically destroys the liver cells - in many cases, the first symptoms show up after 20-30 years.
Timely prevention, such as regular inspections, is therefore essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those who had undergone a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooed people.
Currently, the number of people suffering from chronic hepatitis C is estimated at 200 million worldwide.
Since the disease is already detectable during a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to see the family doctor at the first signs of unknown origin.
Recognized in time, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, thereby banning the risk of infection and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30th is World Hepatitis Day, held for the first time by patient representatives worldwide in 2004.
The aim of the action is to increase awareness of this chronic liver inflammation caused by viruses, its formation and the importance of early detection.
Do believers have less pain?
As recent research shows, religious belief is thought to be a “pain-killer” that has already facilitated the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University have conducted an interesting experiment: It was investigated to what extent belief in God affects the feeling of pain in man, the British newspaper Telegraph reported.
In the course of the rather bizarre investigation, 12 believers and atheists each received electroshocks while studying a painting of the Mother of God.
As the results showed, the faithful were able to eliminate the majority of the pain.
Using brain scan technology, it was even proven that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for controlling pain.
The study was the first in a research project in which, in addition to scientists, philosophers and theologians from various departments of the university participated.
During the test, a sparkling device was attached to the left hand of the subjects, which gave off the electric shocks.
Participants were asked to concentrate heavily on two paintings: on the one hand a picture of the Mother of God, painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, and on the other hand Leonardo da Vinci's "Dame mit dem Hermelin".
The researchers hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would evoke some sort of religious trance among the faithful while they chose da Vinci’s image because it was hardly different from the other painting and was found to be reassuring.
The subjects spent half an hour each in an MRI scanner, receiving a total of 20 electric shocks in four stages during this time, while either watching the religious or the other painting.
The Catholics reported that they felt “safe” at the sight of the Mother of God, as if they had been “cared for,” and they felt “rest and peace.”
While contemplating the religious painting, they reported about 12% less pain than when they had Leonardo’s work in mind.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, said that similar effects could also be produced with other, powerful images, even among the atheists, you just had to find the corresponding photo.
"We would have to find an image that triggers very positive sensations, such as a mother or a father," the psychologist said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
“Practicing faith should change our personality, and it does so in many cases,” Wright said.
After these excellent results, there remains only the question of what effect a Madonna image of Leonardo or another comparable painter would have on the pain regulation of the faithful.
Would the high-quality Virgin Mary achieve even better results?
