Smart car imitates the flight of the bumblebee
What would be the best way to develop new technologies to avoid accidents if not to imitate the obstacle sensors from nature?
For example, bees.
At CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was presented, in which Nissan engineers were inspired by bumblebees in the creation of new accident avoiding systems.
In collaboration with Tokyo University, Nissan has built the BR23C car-driven biomimetic system, a mini-car equipped with the characteristics of the bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own, oval “private area,” which is very similar to our own “protective shield,” said Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, at the exhibition.
The composite eye of the bee, which can see in any direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role.
To mimic the function of the composite eye, the researchers adopted the idea of the laser-controlled distance meter.
This identifies obstacles from the BR23C in a field of vision of 180 degrees within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision-avoiding process.
The obstacle is recorded in fractions of a second, and the autorobot immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of the bees by turning the tires around the appropriate angle.
In contrast to previous systems, this maneuver takes place purely instinctively.
“If it weren’t, the autorobot wouldn’t be able to respond fast enough to avoid the obstacles,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the autorobot project.
The system must act instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer within which accidents are currently considered unavoidable.
The entire process must reflect the behavior of the bees when they dodge other bees.
And that has to happen in a fraction of a second.
However, in contrast to the bees, dodging can not take place upwards, downwards, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, and specifically only in the direction of the maneuverability of the tires.
While there are endless possibilities for the bees to avoid other bees, the researchers could only use the autorobot to rotate, or to accelerate and slow down.
The BR23C contains lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy-efficient, and therefore have a longer service life than conventional lithium-ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it depends on the instinctive, intelligent response, and less on the processing of the data, and even less on the ability to store it.
This device only needs to process a few inputs per second and respond accordingly.
It does not need to store them, or produce an intuitive, logical response based on previous maneuvers, so that it only requires a handful of KB memory.
There is no need for gigabyte and megabyte-heavy memories.
This is the first step in the development of immediate collision avoidance technology, which Nissan estimates will be in production as standard within the next ten years.
Another application could find the technology in GPS satellite navigation by deliberately guiding the driver around obstacles and thus leading him to the destination.
