Napolitano: ‘Prevention of accidents at work is crucial’
Every day in Italy, 2,500 work accidents occur, three people die and 27 remain incapacitated for life.
For 2007, data from the Inail (Istituto nazionale contro gli infortuni sul lavoro) confirm that the fatal accidents at work were around 1200.
These numbers prove the seriousness of a phenomenon that causes almost twice as many deaths as those caused by murders.
Today, the Anmil (Associazione Nazionale Mutilati e Invalidi del Lavoro) in all provinces of Italy will celebrate the 58th National Day for the victims of work accidents in order to draw the attention of social institutions and the media to this dramatic situation.
"The worrying data disseminated by Anmil and the tragic news of these days confirm the crucial importance of prevention in the workplace," confirmed the President of the Republic of Giorgio Napolitano in his communication to the President of the Amil (Associazione nazionale mutilati ed invalidi del lavoro) Pietro Mercandelli.
The head of state expresses his "great appreciation for the constant commitment to prevention in the workplace, to protecting the injured workers, to helping the families of the victims and to raising awareness of public opinion".
"An outrageous 'bastard' has risen to this; understandable in the case of tragedies that, in terms of their magnitude, trigger some swirling in the media and public participation, but everyday reality often confronts us with dramatic events that can even be repeated in their own dynamics."
Napolitano does not hide that "there is in any case also a resource problem: it must be invested decisively in education and information."
The numerous initiatives for more direct awareness in school settings are of particular importance to young people who are feeding on the world of work.
It is our duty to focus attention on this phenomenon and not to distract from its social seriousness, and we must put in place and improve a legislative standard.
For his part, the President of the Chamber, Gianfranco Fini, stressed "how the phenomenon of work-related deaths creates an urgent social emergency that offends the consciences of all of us and forces all institutions to work towards firm rules that aim to end the problem".
“The data from the work accidents seem to signal a slight improvement, but this does not rule out that the number of work-related deaths is far too high,” said Anmil President Pietro Mercandelli.
"We don't want this 'positive tendency' to mean less attention. That's exactly what causes the tragedy in the end."
"It's like thinking that you're basically doing too little to deal with the phenomenon of accidents. You can fight it through different actions.
In our opinion, stronger controls and inspections are necessary – according to Mercandelli; but also stronger measures to educate the workers who are already starting in school.”
"Another effort is necessary - he adds - in terms of communication and sensitization of public opinion.
But above all, a greater sense of responsibility on the part of employers towards a phenomenon that represents a social emergency is required."
Mercandelli also commented on "the progressive deterioration of protection for victims of accidents at work" and denounced the "abolition of the social system against which we have been fighting in recent years".
The aim is, therefore, to return to the worker a guarantee of insurance, so that the fate of the victim of a work accident does not become dependent on voluntary or accidental donations, which are decided from time to time by a legislator.
Mp3 Player under Indictment: Risk of Hearing Damage
Listening to loud music over a longer period of time with portable music devices, such as MP3 players, can lead to permanent hearing damage.
In a report published today in Brussels, the European Commission quotes the opinion of the Csrseri (Scientific Committee on Current and Recently Identified Health Risks) of the EU.
"The report shows that 5-10% of those who listen to loud music with portable music devices for at least five years a week for more than one hour a day risk permanent loss of hearing."
“I’m worried that such a large number of teens, who usually put portable music devices and mobile phones at a high volume, irretrievably damage their hearing without knowing it,” said Meglena Kuneva.
"The scientific findings - it is said on the part of the European Union - show a clear risk, which pushes for rapid action.
What really matters is to sensitize consumers and make this information a common good.
In view of these scientific findings, we need to review the already existing control systems so that they are fully effective and keep up with the new technology."
Brussels had commissioned the independent scientific committee in light of the widespread use of portable music devices among young people.
"Scientists - concludes the EU Communication - confirm that one is rightly concerned and that the European Commission, together with the other EU members and those concerned, will now examine the necessary measures to better protect children and young people from the noise coming from portable music devices and similar devices".
There is already a European standard that limits the level of noise from portable music devices to 100 dB, and concerns about the damage that could be caused by excessive noise.
These damages can be very limited by resorting to solutions such as reducing the volume and the length of noise exposure.
In its report, the EU’s Scientific Committee points out that if the users of portable music devices only listen to loud music for five hours a week (more than 89 decibels) so that the legal limits that apply to the maximum noise level at work are already exceeded.
Those who cross this line of music risk the complete loss of hearing within five years.
This is 5-10% of the users of such devices, whose number can be estimated at between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
Roma, Alemanno launches "Commission for the Future of the Capital"
We'll start today, we'll be over in March, we'll take stock in June.
This is the procedure set by the Capitol for the work of the Commission for the Future of the Capital of Rome, which met this morning in the new seat behind the Caracalla thermal baths.
In six months, President Marzano and the other 49 members of the Commission will work out the guidelines for Rome.
Once the project is completed, the City Council and the Municipal Council will evaluate the analyses and projects in order to be able to present the strategic plan for Rome with the "official stamp" of the Capitol and Mayor Gianni Alemanno in June.
"The Commission is absolutely independent and all political, social and cultural opinions are represented in it," - stresses Alemanno. "It will propose a development plan for Rome, whose political responsibility will remain with the city council and the municipal council.
There is no redistribution of responsibilities, only the will to have a place where one can develop a large project for Rome.
In March, their task will be completed and the Commission will dissolve again, as such a project must have a time-determined endpoint.
In June, the mayor announced, we will present the strategic plan in which we will use the work done by the Commission."
Anyone who questions the competence of the Commission, because their opinion is not binding, answers Alemanno: "Everything depends on the work that the Commission will do and on the quality of its proposals.
If, like the Attali Commission in France, it delivers quality results – and this will certainly be the case in Rome – then its contribution will be fundamental.
Too often, politics deals with the everyday problems and emergencies that occur from time to time.
We, on the other hand, want to have a longer period of time in view, in order to work seriously on the development of Rome and the future of the city in a deeper perspective."
The mayor of Rome attaches great importance to clarifying the following: "This commission is neither a useless institution nor a wreck: it is absolutely free, it will not cost the Roman citizens a penny and it will make us think. It will employ the best minds of the capital".
According to Alemanno, "it is necessary to have a strategic plan that is neither hermetic nor static in order to enable our city to take a quality leap - which it really needs - and thus to take a joint step into the future."
A future, according to the mayor of Rome, which “will not only limit itself to the current municipal borders, but will look much further”, not only in terms of Rome’s role as a metropolis and political capital of Italy, but also as a future capital of Europe and the Mediterranean.”
