The elite is in danger.
The phenomenon had been revealed a few days ago when the Chamber of Deputies voted against the $700 billion savings package from the White House: A large part of Americans were and are more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday’s edition of the New York Times, which reports how the crisis is splitting up the Republican party, which is increasingly splitting into its old and moderate East Coast soul, which has always favored state institutions and the business community, and those neoconservatives who are “hostile to those in Washington” and the financial world, and are gaining voters, especially in the south and central states.
This part of the party owes its rise above all to the voice of the one I mentioned above.
This example, however, is only a small part of the major changes that the current economic earthquake is announcing or even already representing: not only in the United States, but throughout the West and perhaps beyond, will it be affected.
Both in the states and in Europe, the crisis seems to speed up the long-awaited events that are finally taking shape and coming to light under these new conditions.
The first of these phenomena is the rediscovery, the unheard of renaissance of the state in connection with a kind of renationalization of the economy.
In fact, the crisis is a decline in banking and financial institutions, which have close ties to foreign countries and at the same time manage an enormous amount of assets of private households that live in a single state.
This means a direct political problem for governments: namely, how to behave towards the families affected, which are also an enormous mass of voters.
So the crisis appears to be global economically, but politically it is almost purely national.
Political internationalism in itself seems to have fallen aside and lost its right to speak: the obvious proof of this has been given by the EU, which, due to its division into various national and international conflicts, does not find a common way.
Therefore, everyone now expects the intervention of their own state; rescue plans, new rules, and especially distribution of aid funds: Since the crisis became more and more serious, only the US is in the economic position to save itself without foreign help.
And in addition to the means, they also have the legitimacy to use them: thus, two conditions that cannot be overstated – under certain circumstances – to which otherwise no international organization and no market will be able to resort in a similar way.
Moreover, the new emphasis placed on the state-national element is in perfect harmony with the ever-increasing importance that has recently been associated in the economy with one of the most closely related sectors: territoriality.
Paradoxically, it is precisely now that we have been so convinced that we have long since entered a networked whole empire, a realm of ever-differentiated technologies, the intangible, that we must at once determine how our future will depend more and more on the essential material things: water, harvest and oil.
These can all be transported from one place to the other in the world, but they are still connected to a narrowly defined piece of earth – a territory.
Therefore, he who has such a territory is in favor of another who lives in a harvestless, waterless or oil-free area.
I now come to the second novelty, which, however, requires a brief insertion.
Who says territory, who says government, who says politics, also says leadership.
In this sense, the financial crisis seems to generate two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, there is the knowledge of the need for respected leadership, i.e. the need for someone who knows how to regulate things.
On the other hand, there is now a wave of indignation over the existing leaderships, especially those of the economy, which have turned out to be inadequate and full of shadow zones.
Finally, there is a deeper and more disturbing aspect: a loss of trust, an intolerance, an image of ineffectiveness, a sense of distance, all aimed at a whole class of managers in Western countries.
It seems to pave the way for the conviction among large sections of the population that it is not only the actions of the social elite, but already their world of ideas, their way of life, their culture in the broadest sense of the word, whose salary presents itself to the majority as ever more alien and outdated.
The demand for leadership, therefore, subterraneanly feeds a branched but powerful movement of disempowering the leading class and the traditional political establishment, manifested in the unforeseen "revolts" of the voters and in the sudden upheaval of the collective state of mind in recent times: starting with the rise of the conservatives in Austria and Bavaria, perhaps playing a role here in the collapse of the Labour Party.
One gets the impression that the old elite, its parties, its programs, but also its rites, magazines, intellectual creditors, some would say its format, has more and more problems of understanding and therefore less representative value in relation to what is going on in the lower social strata of the West today, and is being amplified and driven from the financial crisis to overdimensionality.
In view of all of this, it would be simply exaggerated to speak of a "rebellion of the masses".
Keeping your eyes wide open is certainly not.
The super glue that rises on walls
Defeat the forces of gravity thanks to an adhesive and climb up walls like Superman.
This is the subject of four American research centers, one of which seems to have almost reached its destination.
With an adhesive applied to an area of only 2.5 sq cm, the researchers succeeded in fixing a 100 kg body on a vertical wall.
The STUDIO – an American journal has published the findings of researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material invented by the research team is a further development of the already used adhesives, which use a special carbon structure, called carbon nanotubes.
"The principle of glue can be imagined as a series of spaghetti tubes arranged in a stack," explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
The scientists have been inspired by the feet of the geckos, which are covered by microscopic hairs that give the animal a perfect hold.
The tests carried out with various materials such as glass teflon and abrasive paper have shown that the new adhesive is ten times stronger than the holding capacity of the feet of the reptiles and at the same time "removes it from the wall without any problems," according to Liming Dai, researcher at the Faculty of Engineering at the University of Dayton.
"This material could be used as a transient adhesive," adds Liming Dai.
Maybe, but the researchers are thinking of a less fascinating benefit, such as the connection of electrical devices, because the nanotubes are also conductors of heat and electricity.
Further areas of application could fall within the field of space travel.
For now, the superheroes have to wait.
THE OTHER TYPE OF RESEARCH – also the University of Berkeley, California, is devoted to a new type of glue.
In an article by the American Chemical Society, the California scientists present a microfibre adhesive that cleans itself from the dust by moving on a surface like hair and thus always maintains perfect adhesion.
Medicines: never take with fruit juice
Beware of grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, which are consumed mainly in summer due to their refreshing quality and vitamin richness, can cause serious health damage if taken at the same time as certain vital medications, as they can have an extreme effect on the absorption of these by the body.
David Bailey, professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, repeatedly points out the risk of both packaged and fresh fruit juices associated with drug intake. At the 236th meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he once again sounded the alarm: A glass of apple, orange or grapefruit juice is enough to reduce the absorption capacity of certain vital medications to the extent that these are practically eliminated from the patient’s health.
Grapefruit juice was already suspected to be responsible for increasing the effects of some drugs such as antibiotics, antiasthmatics, cardiovascular drugs, anxiolytic and neurological drugs, up to toxic levels.
The same agency of the drug had warned doctors and patients in a report two years ago of the dangers of this mix, stressing to pay attention to what is drunk in conjunction with drugs such as diazepane or metadone.
IT IS NOT ONLY GRAPE FRUIT – According to experts, orange juice and apple juice also contain substances that can inhibit the drugs.
The list of active ingredients inhibited by the fruit juices is long.
Michele Carruba, Director of the University of Milan, said: "Such results are usually immediately forwarded to the various international manufacturers who are free to change consumer information.
Therefore, it is advisable to always read the package leaflet and, if there are any uncertainties, not to be afraid to ask a pharmacist or doctor," emphasizes the expert of the Ansa agency.
