Open Office, the third version of the "Anti-Microsoft" package
The day of the release of OpenOffice.org 3.0 has come; the open source software is gaining an ever-increasing number of users as a free replacement for Microsoft’s Office, both at home and in the office, both among freelancers and in the public administration.
After a year of intensive work by the voluntary developers, which is monitored by SUN Microsystems, the new Open Office now presents itself with some novelties to the audience: in addition to a revised and now more spartanly designed initial menu, finally a fundamentally guaranteed compatibility with Apple's operating system Mac OS x is achieved, as well as the support for the new ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2 format, i.e. the latest standard ISO version, given.
There was also attention to compatibility with Microsoft's Office 2007, whose new formats (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx) can be read by OpenOffice.
Also interesting are some new features, such as the one that allows to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations, which makes it easier to send via email, including the possibility to import PDF files into graphics editing modules and at the same time preserve the original appearance of the page.
In this way, it is now possible to generate "hybrid" PDF files, which extend the typical graphics of the Adobe format by the elements of a table and a word processing system.
Collaboration is one of the most enhanced elements of the applications: tables can now be edited by multiple users, avoiding conflicts during changes; in the case of the word processing system, each editor is assigned a phrase to ensure a better correction process.
Some companies are in the process of publishing various features of OpenOffice on the internet (on the cloud), while in the coming weeks the final result is to be made public.
The Italian version is available for download at the following link: http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html. Thus it follows the English version, which has been on the mirrors since Friday.
Except for Windows and Mac OS, the program is also available for the Linux operating system.
On request, the installation CD can be sent home or to the office.
However, if freedom of charge can be an incentive for the distribution of the program in private households, it is also in the business sector where OpenOffice could succeed: after all, various public administration and schools have already switched to OpenOffice.
In fact, there is not even a lack of a training offer, which means optimal help for small and medium-sized enterprises, and thus even opens up business prospects.
OpenOffice is composed of five main components: Writer, the Word-appropriate text creation program; Calc, the table program that aims to displace Excel; Impress, for creating presentations such as with PowerPoint; Dbase for operating databases instead of the more familiar Access; and finally Draw, a graphic module.
The goal for 2008 is to reach 5 million downloads – a goal that can easily be exceeded with 3 million and 600 thousand already reached.
