Farewell to the old cinema Paradiso – the cities close their historic cinemas
The historic cinemas close due to the favored multiplex cinemas.
“A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes.”
This image by director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is happening at the moment in the major urban centers of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of excluding cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multi-room complexes in the periphery, means death in the long run for the one-room cinema in the center. A process that not only seems inevitable and irrevocable, but also bears the characteristics of a cultural crime.
It is like losing a friend with whom you have traveled a piece of road full of emotions,” says the director of the film “Nuovo Cinema Paradiso”, which brought him the Oskar and the Cannes Grand Prix 20 years ago. It is the story of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a probably lost cinema world.
The figures provided by Anec, the central trade association, speak a clear language: over the past five years, the vast number of 316 traditional cinemas have had to close; this tick paid for the most part the cinemas in the major cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the most affected regions are Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This proves that the main culprits are the multiplex cinemas, because it is precisely these three regions in which the largest number of these modern cinemas has been registered: with 195 in the last 5 years, Lombardy leads the lists, 81 in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way," says Paolo Protti, President of Anec, "though it is useful that new structures also emerge, the preservation of the already existing one comes first, because if a hall in the city closes, not all its regular customers are willing to visit a multiplex cinema in the periphery instead of the old one.
And here the lack of budget for the fund of the trade association remains out of the box: the debt burden recorded by the state is about 10 million euros.
It is a disgrace from the ethical point of view that the government does not comply with existing laws.
In order to maintain the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros per year would be needed."
It is interesting to note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, due to the fears surrounding the old cinemas, decided to protect them by means of an agreement between the municipality and the Anec; it is the first such agreement in Italy that aims to protect and support traditional cinemas, both in the historical center and in the periphery.
Among the measures foreseen are also tax advantages for cinema operators and benefits for the public regarding local transport: it will be allowed to drive to the restricted areas of the center and also to park at cheaper parking fees.
“It’s a gratifying initiative,” says Giuseppe Tornatore, “I hope that other cities will follow our example and also design new concepts.
Certainly, however, we also need better audio and video equipment in order to be able to do something against the superpower of the multiplex halls, because after all, today’s audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema has always been an important issue for me: the closure of the "Supercinema" of Baghiera, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the decisive point that led me to found the "Nuovo cinema Paradiso", even though I had been playing with the thought for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years; when I pass by the Rialto or the Quirinale in the Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn aside to avoid having to see the dusty posters.
The links between politics and 'Ndrangheta lead to the arrest of the mayor of Gioia Tauro
"The mayor of Gioia Tauro was prepared to adapt the decisions of the municipality to the interests of the Piromalli Mafia Group.
The allegations of Calabria’s lawyers against Mayor Giorgio Dal Torrione and his deputy Rosario Schiavone of the municipality of Gioia Tauro, who were arrested this morning for involvement in mafia shops, are serious.
Gioacchino Piromalli, the older mediator between the clan and the public administration, and his nephew, was also handcuffed: the lawyer, who bears the same name as the clan’s boss, had already been sentenced to a compensation amount of 10 million euros for involvement in criminal associations of the mafia at the time.
“Disregarding any kind of moral and legal norm,” the lawyers write, “the two local administrations had decided to pay the lawyer Piromalli money for consulting activities.”
“This allowed the mafia group – according to the judges – to enter the town halls officially and to co-determine the policy of public administration.”
The president of the Calabria Regional Committee, Agazio Loiero, does not deny that in his region "it is anything but an exception to encounter connections between local administrations and organised crime." "There are places where the concentration of the mafia is greater than in others where such connections are practically inevitable.
But there are also local politicians who resist the pressure of the 'Ndrangheta: heroes who maintain a white vest."
The arrests of this morning follow those of last July, with which, according to police, the clan Piromalli was beheaded.
Since the end of last April, the municipal council of Gioia Tauro had been dissolved, but already in 1991 – and even then due to alleged links between organized crime and the local administration – the local politicians had been removed from their municipal offices.
Giorgio Dal Torrione, then mayor of the Udc, was elected head of the centre-right coalition after the 2006 election.
He shouted scandal when the prefecture ordered the dissolution of the municipal council.
He appealed to Vice Minister Marco Minniti, whom he accused of having invented everything for political-strategic reasons, but the judges stated in connection with this morning’s arrest warrant that the Piromalli clan had even dared to request a change to the A3 project.
From an interception related to the Dal Torrione case, there has been a willingness to respond to the wishes of an entrepreneur who is known to be a representative of the large group around the Piromalli – thus making the public administration’s actions identical to the interests of this clan.”
When the energy comes from the waves, the big ones suddenly run up.
It is an unblemished source of money covering over 70% of the planet’s surface, and it is only now that the world’s major energy companies seem to understand this.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that everyone is now looking at, and is also looking to occupy, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and studied for 70 years; these studies have not by chance intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil collapsed around 1980, the idea of marine energy was gassed, but now environmental organizations and the rising price of oil are pushing for new impetus in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the world’s energy needs could be met by the energy generated by ocean waves.
This would equal twice the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, there are the currents and tides.
Giants in the attack.
The first company to rely on marine energy is Enersis, which signed a contract for the construction of a power plant in northern Portugal in 2005.
When this news was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies from the traditional energy industry are now relying on marine energy production.
“Chevron is investigating these technologies,” said the spokesman for a company known to the U.S. giant in the Wall Street Journal, “and is considering the possibility of working with us.”
This is about obtaining an approval from the American Energy Commission, which is necessary to start a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a not to be underestimated sign, especially when you consider that the U.S. continues to extract oil in Alaska, and President Bush recently launched plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, the companies Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey are also investing in the new industry; if the details are not known, observers speak of increasing interest.
Still better technologies.
Experts speak of a technology still underway, not least because the last doubts on the part of environmentalists have not yet been clarified.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and Scotland are of a rather small dimension and do not seem to cause any serious ecological problems.
However, in order to produce energy on a large scale, technologies with a much greater impact on the environment are needed.
There are several options: Ocean Power uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The thrust of the shafts, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the floats via pistons and cylinders.
This drives a turbine, which in turn operates a generator.
The electricity is then sent to the coast via underwater pipelines.
So far, there are four planned installations of this type, which are only waiting for government approval. Part of the energy gained could also be used for military facilities.
Verdant Power, however, already produces energy for a department store and a parking lot using submarine turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movements during the tides drives the turbines, which feed the generator as a result of the resulting rotational movement.
According to Verdant, a long line of potential clients is already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Electricity Generation Research, a particular interest deserves the potential that is present in the tides right now.
Although it is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are better predictable than wind currents, sunlight and also waves, and therefore a more trustworthy source of electricity.
It is tidal energy in particular that led states like New York, Maine and Alaska, as well as other coastal states, to invest $7.5 million in 2008 – up to 35 million are already planned for 2009.
